1:---
2:title: "The Intuitive Inadequacy of Classical Statistics"
3:year: 1984
4:abstract: >
5:  In this talk, Jaynes explores the differences between "classical" (frequentist)
6:  and Bayesian statistics. He argues that many of the perceived inadequacies in
7:  Bayesian methods are actually misapplications or ideological barriers, and that
8:  Bayesian methods provide a more robust and unified framework for inference, 
9:  especially in generalized inverse problems where orthodox methods fail.
10:author: ["E.T. Jaynes"]
11:categories: ["Foundations of Probability & Bayesian Inference"]
12:tags: ["classical statistics", "Bayesian statistics", "frequentism", "generalized inverse problems", "maximum entropy", "medical diagnosis", "scientific objectivity"]
13:---
14:## INTRODUCTION
15:The title of this talk, suggested to me in Professor Agazzi's kind
16:letter of invitation, caused a moment of uncertainty. What variety of
17:statistics is meant by "classical"? J. R. Oppenheimer [1955] held that
18:in science the word "classical" has a special meaning: "[...] it
